  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the best way to start contributing to open source is not by hunting for “Good First Issue” labels, but by fixing problems you’ve already solved yourself—especially documentation gaps or simple code improvements based on your own struggles. The author, an experienced contributor to major projects like Node.js and Docker, advises scanning your dependency files for libraries that caused frustration, then using your firsthand experience to help others avoid the same pain. Written in an enthusiastic, tutorial-like tone with emojis and bold text, the piece targets developers who find conventional contribution advice intimidating, framing the process as a three-step reflection on past challenges rather than a search for new ones.",
